@flexiarg vsatlatarium/dome-projection
@title Dome Projection as Reading Frame
@audience narrative system designers, VSAT collaborators
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [🔭/天]
@references [vsatlas/connected-story-world vsatlas/interpretive-views]

! conclusion:
  Project story constellations onto a dome surface so the viewer occupies a
  privileged interior position — reading outward rather than inspecting
  from above.

  + context: You are choosing a spatial metaphor for browsing a connected story world. This does not apply when the corpus is small enough that a flat list suffices.
  + IF:
    A collection of linked stories needs a spatial reading frame that
    communicates immersion and equal proximity.

  + HOWEVER:
    Flat graphs or tree views impose implicit hierarchies and lose the
    sense of being surrounded by a world.

  + THEN:
    Map story clusters onto the inner surface of a sphere (planetarium
    model) so the viewer looks outward at the constellation from its
    centre, with drag-to-rotate giving access to the full sky.

  + BECAUSE:
    The dome equalises distance — every story is the same radius away,
    and orientation replaces ranking as the primary navigation axis.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM planetarium mode — implemented and tested on Quest 2]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Measure whether dome vs flat-list affects exploration breadth (stories visited per session).]
    next[Test with screen-reader users to define a non-visual equivalent of dome orientation.]
